76561198007339991,Recommended,268400,27797087,"Posted: 27 November, 2016",all,Dimwit [WN] / AlJabberwock,"TL:DR ~ you don't need any of these reviews.  Go watch a few of ReneMesis' YT playthroughs of the first campaign.  You either are an addict waiting to happen, or you really aren't.  Watching our good Norwegian commentator celebrate or bemoan his fate will tell you which you are.  And that's probably what you came down here for anyway.If, however, you want to do it the hard way, or look for ' Review Rembrandts ' painting word pictures with light... well.God help you.REVIEWAs many reviews here suggest, this game shows a clear descendance from Panzer General (for those who remember that venerable series).  Those older still, will recognize the style as the computerized form of SPI games or Avalon HIll's Squad Leader Series =  Boardgames with cardboard maps and real dice, so absorbing that shouts and hand slamming could punctuate play, with teams of players hanging on every die roll - cursing and posturing at foul or fair fortune.I love this game, so for those who want the perspective of a fan, I will put up the main things that I respctfully still find some fault with - and later why those didn;t keep me from acquiring and enjoying the title.Problems1)This game brings all that good stuff back I mention in the first para.. but obviously with the ease and greater detail possible only in a computerized instance.  While Panzer Corps is every bit as addictive as I remember those old games being this comes at a price as multiplayer is only asynchronous PBEM and only 1v1.  A shame, even if it is understandable with the limited objectives of the designers, this should not keep serious players from considering this title if they have the necessary green.  And that's another thing...2)At the time of thie writing, the regular price for this aging title is simply too high, with all the DLCs and the base game still costing $140 US when not on sale.  You need those DLCs to play the grand campaign which is by far the queen of the chessboard of experiences of the title, and would leave a big hollow place in one's game world not to have.  We purchased a few copies of this while on a 70% sale so the total bundle amounted to around the price of a regular Triple A title.  Thats for a title that is 5 years old, even if it IS a huge title in terms of content and an incredible amount of work is contained in it.  Many people probably don't care about large segments of that body of work... regardless of the depth it may add to the game experience.3)Repetition of scenario format and victory conditions makes some people go 'spla' and it can be a bit annoying at times since other means of accomplishing a scenario objective clearly offer themselves, and any afficianado of WW2 can think of dozens of objectives in history that could be modeled easily enough.Benefits1)Library.  The detalied library of all the equipment provided in the game is an amazing resource and is accompanied by enlargeable diagrams.2)This highlights a lot of the ways in which the game models supply, fuel, and replacement.  It feels right, and the various equipment and formations feel properly weighted because of that research as well as clearly, a great deal of playtesting.3)There are few bugs.  No show stoppers.  Weird.  (heh !)4)WHen its on sale its a good value.  Many many units, and plenty of diversity.5)Granular control and difficulty settings.6)Not a computer hog, and while it is fun to look at, its no eye candy maven.  If you are looking for something to throw tri-sli at, you've taken a wrong turn somewhere...  (Hah ha ha ha!)7)If you leave it set to reasonable variation of results (die roll), there will be those times you WILL be grumpy and cry out loud... put your face in your palm, and reel so far back... ""that you can clutch a fringe or two of the windy past"" when we rolled real dice, and shouted ""GODDA--- uhhhh ---NICE!""Buy it on sale. but do get it if watching a playthrough makes you want to watch another one.  :)  ~'Crazy Uncle' Al"
