76561198089044310,Recommended,268400,20957740,"Posted: 4 February, 2016",all,rubyjuno,"I remember a young birthday when I used my money to buy some Airfix Matildas to help out against the Airfix Panzers on my tabletop desert battlefield. That was over 40 years ago and how things have changed... After progressing through the ZX Spectrum and Atari ST, I finally arrived at a 386DX and MS-DOS 5, a platform that was to develop into the best and most versatile gaming system the world has to offer.There was Perfect General, Panzer General, History Line to name a few. I loved the simplicity of Panzer General 2 and Battle Isle 2 over the wargames with more complex rules, preferring to play than read rule books. Last year I discovered Panzer Corps and was amazed at how easy it was to pick up and play, it must be the most accesible wargame ever.I've now played through the base game, and went back and replayed it a couple a times to make sure I had a go at all of the scenarios. I read a few tips to sharpen my game and have worked out the whole combined arms thing. I've moved on to Africa Korps on my laptop but I'm replaying the original game on my desktop on Field Marshal diffculty (my first go was on Colonel). I've bought all the DLC up to and including Sea Lion as I know it's going to take me a long time to tire of it.For the hard core wargamer who likes a thick book of rules and calling up off map artillery and air support, ensuring tanks are facing the right way and every realism nailed down, Panzer Corps might be too simplistic. But for a more casual wargamer who wants to flick through a thin rule book and do his learning on the battlefield, it's perfect. There's a great support community on the Slitherine website, and DLC keeps getting released. Highly recommended for those who want to play a solid wargame without having to go on a course first."
