,Recommended,268400,9676351,"Posted: 30 March, 2014",all,Lisbon,"Panzer Corps is a turn-based strategy or ‘wargame’. Each scenario you are tasked with deploying your troops and taking a set number of objectives across the map. Units earn experience and can be upgraded during the deployment phase with any new equipment unlocked. This is done using prestige points that you acquire by completing objectives and are also used to reinforce units during battle when they lose strength. Prestige points are persistent throughout the campaign meaning spending all of your points in one battle may not be wise as you are effectively depleting your resources for the next engagement; although you do receive some at the beginning of each scenario, what you have carries over.The graphics of Panzer Corps are fairly basic although nice to look at with each type of unit distinguishable from each other. Sounds can also said to be somewhat basic as each unit type has a single sound that is played during movement and attack. This may sound repetitive however after 18 hours of playing Panzer Corps I can say this has yet to bother me. The interface is effective at doing the job and gives you access to all of the information you need without being intrusive.Panzer Corps strikes a great balance between depth and accessibility and offers a great entry point into wargames for the uninitiated. The gameplay is addictive and the visuals and audio serve the game well, while the multiplayer uses a play-by-email method so multiple games can be played at once over the course of a few or more days.Panzer Corps has quickly become one of my favourite games and I would happily recommend it to anyone."
76561197964559256,Recommended,268400,9442136,"Posted: 12 March, 2014",all,Keg,"Great to see the Panzer Corps series has finally come to steam.  It is one of the best turn based WW2 strategy games that I have ever played. It is easy to get into but has tactical depth.  Large variety of units to build your core army with throughout the game, there is nothing like having an early panzer crew survive long enough that they are a vetern Tiger crew by the games end.  Only downside is the Afrika Corps and Allied Corps are not stand alone because the original Panzer Corps is made obsolete by the Grand Campaign DLCs.  The Grand Campaign DLCs are by far the best value in each being a whole campaign in which your core units are saved and can be carried over to the next chapter of the war.  Allied Corps is great and allows you to play the western Allies starting in North Africa until victory in Western Europe.  Afrika Corps is great and featres some of the more challenging battles in the series while focusing on DAK and Italian forces in North Africa.  Great to finally see Slitherine/Matrix games apearing on steam for the historical strategy gaming crowd."
