76561197999888759,Not Recommended,268400,35519654,Posted: 6 October,all,fish,"This is a great base game held back by designer wheraboosim on an incredible scale. If you enjoy rolling over things with Nazi armor, you'll have a great time. If you'd like to play as the groups that crushed the Nazis like a bug, such as the Americans, Soviets or British, you'll be fighting an enemy with many times the number of overstatted Panthers, Tigers and King Tigers than you get Shermans or T34s or Cromwells. And they'll do it while flooding the skies with more planes than you've ever seen outside of the Bagration mission.Vastly more effort is spent on mission design and content for the Nazi campaigns. The Allied content is perfunctory at best.The actual combat has issues too. Combat stats as reported by the game are largely lies. Your results are essentially random and incredibly spikey. A battle where you are likely to get 7 kills and no losses can flip to you losing 7 strength and the enemy losing nothing. While this is fine in large scale -- and much better designed -- operational wargames like Decisive Campaigns : Barbarossa, in games where your force count is a couple dozen at the end of the game the fate of an entire campaign can hinge on whether or not RNG decides to stuff a broom up up your rear and wiggle it around. I had one missions where I lost three units fortified on hills to enemy infantry that in the previous turn I was predicted likely to beat on the attack. Why? Because RNG hates me.Order of Battle : WW2 is a much, much better game with much more predictable battles, a more complex game environment and a far better UI. It also doesn't descend into the unholy depths of Nazi tank wank like this game does."
